      "question": "A train travels at a certain average speed for a distance of $540 \\text{ km}$. If the speed of the train is increased by $9 \\text{ km/hr}$, the journey would have taken $2 \\text{ hours}$ less. Find the original average speed of the train. Also, find the time taken if the train travels at the increased speed.",
      "answer": "Original speed = $45 \\text{ km/hr}$, Time taken at increased speed = $10 \\text{ hours}$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the original speed of the train be $x \\text{ km/hr}$.",
          "The time taken to cover $540 \\text{ km}$ at original speed is $t_1 = 540/x \\text{ hours}$.",
          "If speed is increased to $(x + 9) \\text{ km/hr}$, the new time taken is $t_2 = 540/(x + 9) \\text{ hours}$.",
          "According to the condition, $t_1 - t_2 = 2$, which implies $540/x - 540/(x + 9) = 2$.",
          "Simplify the equation to form the quadratic $x^2 + 9x - 2430 = 0$.",
          "Factorise the quadratic equation to find $x = 45$ (rejecting negative speed).",
          "Calculate the final time taken at the increased speed using $540/(45 + 9)$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$t_1 = \\frac{540}{x} \\text{ and } t_2 = \\frac{540}{x+9} \\\\ \\frac{540}{x} - \\frac{540}{x+9} = 2 \\\\ 540 \\left( \\frac{x+9-x}{x(x+9)} \\right) = 2 \\\\ 540 \\times 9 = 2(x^2 + 9x) \\\\ 2430 = x^2 + 9x \\\\ x^2 + 9x - 2430 = 0 \\\\ x^2 + 54x - 45x - 2430 = 0 \\\\ x(x+54) - 45(x+54) = 0 \\\\ (x-45)(x+54) = 0 \\\\ x = 45 \\text{ or } x = -54 \\\\ \\text{Original speed } x = 45 \\text{ km/hr} \\\\ \\text{Increased speed time} = \\frac{540}{45+9} = \\frac{540}{54} = 10 \\text{ hours}$"
      },
